{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SZLK8Zhua7u6We7yVejosU","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/16-6-story-flow-execution.md`.\n\n**Story Details:**\n- Story ID: 16.6\n- Story Key: 16-6-story-flow-execution\n- File: `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/16-6-story-flow-execution.md`\n- Status: ready-for-dev\n\nPer instructions, I did NOT modify `sprint-status.yaml`, did NOT run `git add`, and did NOT run `git commit`.\n\n**Verification Tier Summary:**\n- All 6 ACs tagged `test-provable` — the change is a one-line swap from `config.workflow.flow` to `config.workflow.storyFlow` in the engine loop, fully verifiable by unit tests with mocked workflows.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- The workflow template file (`workflow.md`) did not exist — the actual workflow definition uses `workflow.yaml` + `instructions.xml`. Adapted to follow `instructions.xml` directives instead.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- Skipped web research step (step 4 of workflow) — no new libraries or frameworks involved. This story is a one-line engine change with tests.\n- Skipped the validation checklist interactive loop (steps 5-8 of `checklist.md`) — the user explicitly said \"Do NOT ask the user any questions.\"\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- The halted/circuit-breaker behavior means telemetry null tasks after a loop block won't execute if the circuit breaker fires. This is documented as expected behavior matching current `flow:` semantics, but could surprise users who expect telemetry to always run. A future story may need a `finally`-style flow step.\n- Grep for `workflow.flow` consumers beyond the engine is called out as a task but could reveal unexpected references.\n\n**Observations:**\n- This is the simplest story in epic 16. `resolveHierarchicalFlow()` from story 16-1 already does all the normalization. The engine c